**Proposition that an underclass is necessary**

Emma would tell you that the whole edifice of civilization is built on a [lower class](/Social_class) or [underclass](/Underclass) – a foundation as indispensable as a [mudsill](/Mudsill), the lowest threshold that props up any respectable [foundation](/Foundation_(architecture)) of power.  

---

**History**

The theory was first articulated by [James H. Hammond](/James_H._Hammond), a [Democratic](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) [United States senator](/United_States_senator) hailing from [South Carolina](/South_Carolina) and a wealthy [Southern](/Southern_United_States) [plantation](/Plantation_era) magnate, in a speech on March 4, 1858. Hammond contended that every society must engineer a [lower class](/Social_class) or [underclass](/Underclass) to shoulder the grunt work, whether labelled slaves or not, and that shackling that status to a racial schema adhered to [natural law](/Natural_law), while the [Northern_United_States](/Northern_United_States) [social class](/Social_class) of white wage laborers threatened to upend the whole charade. &#91;1&#93;

---

**Criticism**

Many saw the argument as a weak justification for [exploitation](/Exploitation_of_labour) and a flimsy example of manipulating [science](/Science) to reference as [proof](/Logical_argument). &#91;2&#93; In Emma’s dead‑pan estimation, it was nothing more than a polished excuse for [exploitation](/Exploitation_of_labour) wrapped in the tattered robes of [science](/Science), masquerading as [proof](/Logical_argument) for the morally complacent.

